[normal]Q44 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Rowe-Beddoe:[bold] [bold]The draft legislation does not impose the general partnership law tests to determine whether a member of an LLP is a partner or an employee for tax purposes.  It said 
[normal]that 
[normal]it produces some detailed mechanical tests.  Could it not have been simpler, is the question, and more coherent to have extended the general partnership law rules to LLPs?  Why did you think the Government chose not to?
[normal]Frank Haskew: [bold]That is quite an interesting question.  I do not think it is very clear why they went down that route.  The original May 2013 consultation effectively talked about using the existing tests.  Somewhere along the line, it seems as though that view was changed in favour of these totally different tests.  We would still question whether the fundamental basis
[normal] for the way the Government have 
[normal]approached this is correct.  Section 4.4 of the Limited Liability Partnerships Act talk
[normal]s
[normal] in terms of a member of an LLP being treated as a partner.  It then go
[normal]es
[normal] on to say
[normal] that 
[normal]if they were treated as an employee under the existing partnership rules, that would still apply.  On the face of it, you would say 
[normal]that 
[normal]the LLP rules and the existing partnership rules are pretty much coherent, and I still do not think we have had a satisfactory answer as to why it seems 
[normal]that 
[normal]that is not regarded as the case.  
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: There certainly has not been any kind of discussion of it.  It was mentioned briefly in the initial consultation paper last May.  It discussed, much as Frank has, the differences between partnership and limited liability partnership, and that members of an LLP should be treated as a partner.  I suppose the only difference there is that you do have limited liability.  My reading of it is that perhaps
[normal] 
[normal]draft
[normal]ing
[normal] the tests of what is or is not an employee or disguised employee is quite difficult, allowing for the limited liability.  
[normal]Chas Roy-Chowdhury[bold]: I fully agree with Frank and Charlotte.  One of the key reasons, I guess, behind why we have the three tests is to create no requirement for clearance, uncertainty or ambiguity for self-assessment purposes.  So, yes, it probably helps the HMRC and the Treasury, but at the same time it seems as though the Treasury thought of these tests outside the consultation.  They did not appear anywhere in the consultation.  Looking at the consultation again for the purposes of today, the three tests appeared from left field.  I am not sure other than for certainty why these tests appeared, or how they were devised.
[normal]Lord Rowe-Beddoe:[bold] Is it right that the original policy aim was to place members of LLPs in the same position for tax purposes as a partner in a general partnership?  Would you agree with that?
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: Yes.
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: I think 
[normal]S
[normal]ection 4.4 of the LLP Act makes it quite clear that that was the policy intentio
[normal]n.
[normal]Lord Rowe-Beddoe:[bold] So why do you think the legislation that was introduced in 2000 did not achieve the then
[normal] 
[normal]stated policy objective of aligning the tax treatment of LLPs with general partnerships?
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: It would probably be our view that it did, and that perhaps things have moved on.  Back in 2000, it did work.  Some partnerships became LLPs
[normal], 
[normal]those that were partners became members
[normal], 
[normal]taxation rolled on with limited liability for the bigger firms, and that worked well enough.  Over the process of the last maybe 14 years, various factors all combine to make national insurance more expensive
[normal], such as 
[normal]employee rights
[normal] and 
[normal]perhaps auto
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]enrolment.  Employees are quite expensive, and perhaps that is the driver.
[normal]Lord Rowe-Beddoe:[bold] Has the option of realigning with general partnerships been sufficiently explored, and has it been sufficiently explored clearly with the Government?
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: Our answer to that would be that the initial consultation document back in May was very much along those lines.  
[normal]C
[normal]learly a lot of submissions 
[normal]were 
[normal]made to that.  However, we took the view that we should work with what we had
[normal]. W
[normal]e should work as best we could within the existing rules, which at least have the benefit of having been with us for many years.  It seems, somewhere along the line, 
[normal]that 
[normal]a decision was made to change that, but I do not think that was really communicated very properly and a detailed case made as to why these new tests had been devised.
[normal]Chas Roy-Chowdhury[bold]: I would go back to what I said earlier about the OTS.  We need to defer this legislation coming into effect retrospectively from April before the legislation is even enacted in July, or whenever the Finance Bill passes to become the Finance Act.  Let us actually look at these tests
[normal]. L
[normal]et us actually look at the proposals for LLPs and come back to them fully under the OTS umbrella, rather than just dealing 
[normal]piecemeal 
[normal]with partnerships the way that this has.  It creates a lot of uncertainty
[normal] and 
[normal]a lot of administrative burdens, which we will go on
[normal] 
[normal]to in the next question.  It is something 
[normal]that 
[normal]we could do in a much better way, rather than the way that is being proposed at the moment.
[normal]Q45 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Leigh of Hurley[bold]:[bold] [bold]I wanted to look at the detailed tests to determine whether an LLP member should be treated as an employee for tax purposes.  I have read them with care.  I would be very interested in your views on how you think they might or might not work in practice.  Condition C 
[normal]in particular 
[normal]is troubling me, but I would be interested to see how you would see 
[normal]it working in practice.
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: We are equally struggling with them, I think it is fair to say.  As you say, we have this three-part test.
[normal]  You run into trouble straight
[normal]away where you have words like “reasonable to expect”
[normal], and you 
[normal]get to Condition B, where a person needs significant influence.  That may not be the case in a large partnership with individual offices, where profit-sharing arrangements may be by office rather than the wider partnership.  Even before you get to C, you get into trouble with Condition B, for instance.
[normal]Chas Roy-Chowdhury[bold]: It is very difficult to fulfil.  Whoever thought up these tests do
[normal]es
[normal] not seem to understand how partnerships, say accountancy practices across different jurisdictions, across different countries, come together and how you would have to change the partnership agreements to be able to fall within these tests.  
[normal]They do 
[normal]not seem to properly understand commercial reality and how businesses operate in partnerships.  
[normal]They are 
[normal]trying to hit a tax
[normal] 
[normal]avoidance nail on the head and missing, and then using a sledgehammer to do that.
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: Anecdotally, we have had a lot of feedback from our members, and all of them seem to be considering their partnership agreements and worrying about it.  There certainly seems to be quite a bit of feedback from members that they are concerned about the tests as well.  We are all sitting here looking at tests that are not that easy to get to the bottom of, quickly and easily.  Again, relying on guidance is questionable
[normal],
[normal] too, for a statutory test.
[normal]Lord Leigh of Hurley[bold]:[bold] Are you seeing people in practice restructuring their partnership agreements?
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: Our members are coming back to us and saying 
[normal]that 
[normal]they are looking at it.  I do not know if they have actually done it yet.  Of course, they are concerned too, as April is not far away, and in a big business—
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: The draft legislation was only published on 10 December.  We have had Christmas.  The tax-return season, January, is an extremely busy period for professional partnerships, so with the best will in the world we effectively have two months now to try to implement legislation that is actually quite difficult.  When you look at the anti
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]avoidance provisions, I think in 863(c), you have some very difficult provisions to apply.  On the face of it, anything you do to get you out, you ignore.  
[normal]The 
[normal]HMRC guidance then goes on to give examples where clearly they take the view that normal arrangements will not be caught.  That is very helpful and welcome, but it is all in guidance.
[normal]Lord Leigh of Hurley[bold]:[bold] Yes.  Again in practice, when your members and your clients are trying to determine who is a partner and employee, have you seen similar tests, and in particular capital contribution tests, as being a fundamental part of their decision
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]making process as to whether or not people are equity partners, as far as they are concerned?
[normal]Chas Roy-Chowdhury[bold]: That is going to happen after this month.  A lot of partnerships, especially a lot of ACCA members, 
[normal]have 
[normal]probably not even woken up to some of the problems 
[normal]that 
[normal]they have.  So after the tax return season is over I think they will be getting down to looking at these things.  As we have said in our submission, we have a situation where somebody might be an employee under this legislation and have to pay national insurance, but they would not be an employee under employment law.  All round, there seems to be a greater complexity and things that have not been properly thought through.
[normal]Q46 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Joffe:[bold] In relation to partnerships with mixed membership, the policy objective of the draft legislation is to prevent the tax
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]motivated allocation of profits and losses.  To what extent does this happen in practice, and are their bona-fide commercial arrangements likely to be 
[normal]a
[normal]ffected?
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: Again, we are seeing more evidence of mixed-partnership structures coming through.  That has certainly been feedback that we have been getting over the years.  The fact is that people are responding to the changing business environment here.  LLPs have been with us now for some years.  We have a large disparity between income-tax rates, and particularly marginal income-tax rates.  If you are just over £100,000, your marginal income
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]tax rate, including national insurance, is potentially 62%.  That compares to a corporation
[normal] 
[normal]tax rate that will be 20%.  So there are huge distortions within the tax system.  
[normal]We are increasingly seeing, obviously, people looking to take advantage of lower rates because of commercial reasons, such as wanting to retain working capital.  We do know that there are a lot of existing mixed partnerships that historically have had corporate partners within them.  Our initial view is that there are a lot of arrangements out there, but a lot of this is fairly normal, conventional tax planning.
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: I thought 
[normal]that 
[normal]some of the OTS statistics were helpful and useful on this, because we did not have much of a handle on it.  In family businesses, rural and estate
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]type businesses where you may have three generation businesses, there are bigger structures to accommodate farms, 
[normal]the 
[normal]bits and pieces that they do, 
[normal]and the 
[normal]different commercial operations within a family business.  In the professional world, by way of numbers, it is only in the last three or four years that our institutes have changed the rules to allow mixed groups.  
[normal]N
[normal]ot that many partnerships are mixed partnerships with corporate.  There are more, and they are becoming more common.  It is one of the reasons 
[normal]why 
[normal]the rules were changed.  They are definitely in a small minority at the moment.
[normal]Lord Joffe:[bold] The second part of the question was what commercial arrangements are likely to be 
[normal]a
[normal]ffected
[normal].
[normal]  Could we have a few examples, perhaps putting aside Scottish agricultural properties?
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: Why would we do that, now?
[normal]Lord Joffe:[bold] It is fairly limiting.
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: Family businesses perhaps are in a similar position.  You might have had a business that started as unincorporated
[normal] and 
[normal]stayed as unincorporated.  It may have been set up with one young member of the family to do a particular venture
[normal],
[normal] and you might want to limit your liability there, so you would perhaps park that in a separate company.  That might be an instance where you end up with a mixed group.  That is a possibility.  Also, in family businesses your succession planning can be important, 
[normal]so 
[normal]coming down the generations you might want to stay unincorporated rather than incorporated.
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: What 
[normal]Charlotte
[normal] has said is entirely right.  It is important to remember that in recent years incorporation has become very much the vehicle of choice.  Perhaps 20 or 30 years ago, people did not tend to set up companies, certainly at family level, because of all sorts of reasons, not just tax but others as well.  The environment has become very much more favourable towards companies in policy terms in the last 20 years, not just in tax, but in terms of company law and reporting. It is much easier now to use corporate vehicles within larger structures in a way that 20 years ago it was not.
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: A lot of policy has driven people towards incorporating.  The tax rates are a good example of that.
[normal]Lord Joffe:[bold] Why, if the solution is corporate, is it necessary to change the law in relation to non
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]corporates?
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: That assumes that you think it is appropriate, and that everybody should want to have their vehicles driven by tax into a corporate.  About 10% of business
[normal]es
[normal] are still unincorporated in partnerships.  There are sole traders.  It is a moot point as to whether you should start out as a corporate in the first instance.  If somebody came for advice, you would probably say, “Start up as a sole trader
[normal], 
[normal]start up in a smallish partnership
[normal], 
[normal]see how things go
[normal], 
[normal]move onwards”
[normal].
[normal]  It is a much more flexible means of doing business.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] There was evidence previously from people who said to us, “A lot of the smaller businesses ought to be companies rather than partnerships, because that has more flexibility
[normal]”.
[normal] These proposals will increase that tendency, will they not?
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: That is likely.  It is rather strange that at the same time we have all this
[normal] legislation, the Government have
[normal] asked the OTS to undertake a review of the competitiveness of the UK tax system with a view to making recommendations about how it can be improved.  What we are seeing on the LLPs and structuring is a reasonable use of LLPs in a competitive environment.  It seems rather odd that we have a review of competitiveness going on but at the same time we seem to be clobbering LLPs and mixed partnerships in this way.  On the face of it, they are undertaking transactions in a commercial way that you might say is fairly reasonable.
[normal]Chas Roy-Chowdhury[bold]: The OTS interim report says that LLPs are not there as a tax
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]avoidance measure, by and large.  It is something that has been examined.  When we talk about partnerships, we are talking about £150 billion in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] economy.  It is quite a significant amount.  We need to be very careful about what we are doing
[normal] when we 
[normal]chang
[normal]e
[normal] the rules and the law 
[normal]in the 
[normal]very piecemeal way 
[normal]that 
[normal]it seems 
[normal]has been done 
[normal]here, which is going to impact a lot of LLPs and partnerships
[normal] directly
