[normal]Q47 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Joffe:[bold] One of the reasons 
[normal]why 
[normal]that has been advanced is
[normal] that 
[normal]there is a move to change the law to allow LLPs to retain capital, one of the consequences of which would be to pay tax at a lower rate.  Now, I wonder why there 
[normal]should 
[normal]be a tax incentive to companies or LLPs to retain profits when they can retain profits in any event at the normal rate of taxation
[normal].
[normal]  Why should there be an additional incentive?  What is the justification?
[normal]Frank Haskew[bold]: Since the previous Government, we have seen a move to encourage the use of companies.  The previous Government and this Government have always been keen to encourage growth and to retain and reinvest as a fundamental policy.  We saw that with the last Government
[normal] and the 
[normal]zero rate of corporation tax.  So there is a policy to try to encourage people to retain earnings.  A mixed partnership is one way of achieving that but within a wider LLP.
[normal]Charlotte Barbour[bold]: A mixed partnership allows you to use the corporate member to retain profits.  That is no different from if you had totally incorporated your whole business.  It allows you to use the legislation in a different way but to achieve the same result.  I do not think you should differentiate between the two.  To me, it is a perfectly sensible proposition that you could retain capital for working capital to reinvest.  Of course, the other thing with mixed partnerships is that they do not always get access to some things that companies have, so that is another reason for allowing them to retain it as working capital.  As and when money comes out into the hands of the individual owners, they are still going to be paying inco
[normal]me tax at whatever their income-
[normal]tax rates are.  It is purely to allow reinvestment, which is one aspect of policy.
